results.notes: Collected with Jacob Kalichman. Growing on the bark of a live Quercus sect. Quercus toward the base of the tree. Growing with Pulverulina ulmicola (DG2108217), cf. Delicatula sp. (DG2108219), Hydropus omphaliiformis, cf. Gymnopus sp. and Clitopilus sp. Caps greyish brown; smooth; innately fibrillose; dry; 2.2 to 8.0 mm wide and 1.5 to 5.6 mm tall. Gills white and very finely adnexed (almost free); slightly intervenose; widely spaced; even. Stems with very fine black pruina; dry; not releasing liquid when cut; 19.3 to 42.1 mm long and 0.4 to 1.4 mm wide. Some stems compressed and twisted. Basal mycelium white and strigose. Cap and stem context white. Odor and taste not distinctive. Clamps lacking in all tissues. Pileipellis a cutis with brown intracellular pigment and a narrow epicutis layer composed of hyaline hyphae. Pileicystidia not clearly differentiated. Caulocystidia abundant; often arranged in fascicles; hyaline or with brown intracellular pigment; clavate, cylindrical, ellipsoid or ovoid. Caulocystidia measurements: (20.2) 25.1 – 37.3 (43.3) × (7.4) 9 – 16.5 (22) µm; Q = (1.2) 1.8 – 3.5 (4.6); N = 30; Me = 30.5 × 13 µm; Qe = 2.5. Lamellar trama weakly dextrinoid. Lactifers present but not common in the lamellar trama. Pleurocystidia similar to cheilocystidia; some lightly encrusted and/or with blunt apical “horns” like the Pleurocystidia of species in Pluteus sect. Pluteus. Pleurocystidia measurements: (34.5) 41.3 – 82.9 (92) × (6.8) 7.9 – 14.2 (27.3) µm; Q = (2.8) 4.4 – 8.1 (8.7); N = 30; Me = 65.6 × 11.2 µm; Qe = 6.1. Cheilocystidia slightly thick-walled; smooth; hyaline; utriform, fusiform, lageniform or clavate. Cheilocystidia measurements: (30.9) 38.8 – 70.7 (77.7) × (6.2) 8.5 – 12.7 (14.8) µm; Q = (3.1) 3.5 – 7.1 (11.3); N = 30; Me = 54.6 × 10.3 µm; Qe = 5.5. Basidia 2-sterigmate (?). Spores smooth, hyaline and apiculate; inamyloid and reaction not changing significantly after 1 hr 20 min; some slightly heart-shaped. Spore measurements: (5.2) 6.9 – 8.3 (9.1) × (5.1) 6.2 – 7.7 (8) µm; Q = 1 – 1.2 (1.3); N = 30; Me = 7.7 × 6.9 µm; Qe = 1.1

results.notes:
Growing abundantly among mosses, grass and bare soil in a mowed clearing anlong the Raceway trail. Acer rubrum, Magnolia acuminata, Fagus grandifolia, Prunus serotina, Liriodendron tulipifera, Carya sp. and Quercus sect. Lobatae present nearby. 2 fruiting bodies out of many found growing attached to buried Carya nut pieces. Caps convex to pulvinate to plane; dry; glabrous; hygrophanous; with translucent-striate margins; 5.0 to 17.7 mm wide and 2.6 to 7.3 mm tall. Young caps without central depressions, developing deep central depressions in age. Gills white; short-decurrent; with 1 to 2 tiers of lamellulae; slightly intervenose. 16 to 20 full-length lamellae reaching the stems. Stems dry, smooth and even; releasing clear liquid when cut; 11.3 to 32.1 mm long and 0.9 to 2.5 mm wide. Some stems laterally compressed. Basal mycelium sparse; white to pale gray; finely strigose. Odor and taste not distinctive. Pileipellis a cutis. Lactifers abundant in the subpellis (?). Lactifers abundant in the stipe trama. Clamps present in the stipe trama. Caulocystidia abundant; hyaline; smooth; utriform, conical, cylindrical or clavate. Caulocystidia measurements: (18.1) 24.7 – 45.3 (59.8) × (6.5) 7.4 – 10.2 (13.3) µm; Q = (2) 2.3 – 5.8 (6.8); N = 30; Me = 35 × 8.6 µm; Qe = 4.1. Lamellar trama inamyloid. Clamps present in the lamellar trama. Lactifers abundant in the lamellar trama. Pleurocystidia scattered and similar to cheilocystidia (?). Cheilocystidia scattered; fusoid-ventricoe; hyaline and smooth. Basidia 4-sterigmate. Spore print white. Spores immediately weakly amyloid, hyaline, smooth and thin-walled. Spore measurements from spore print: (5.8) 6 – 8.3 (9.1) × (3.1) 3.3 – 4.3 (5.3) µm; Q = (1.5) 1.6 – 2.1 (2.3); N = 30; Me = 7.1 × 3.8 µm; Qe = 1.9.

results.notes:
A NJMA collection made by Brandon Roddy in deciduous woods of the park.
The morphology can be inferred from the pics, but I took detailed notes anyway:
Cap 5.7 cm wide (footprint), subconvex, with a broad central depression, dark vibrant red (oac 553/oac 607); cuticle peeling only at margin to 0.5 cm max; flesh 3-4 mm thick above stipe, staining reddish-brown upon exposure to air; gills close, with no forking, creamy en mass (Q in Kibby/Fatto?), short gills very scant. Stipe 7.5 cm long, uniformly 1.4 cm wide, but narrowing at the rounded base, S-shaped; surface whitish, discoloring grayish-brown in handling, deeper wounds stain brown to very slowly dark brown to blackish-brown (see pic); flesh already gray-brown to reddish brown when sectioned, colors turning darker over time. Taste mild, odor nill to faintly pleasant.
Based on these observations, the code in Kibby & Fatto is AHKNQTV, keying out to Group 3 (cinerascens, decolorans, graveolens, rubriceps), but the descriptions of these species are not in good agreement with Brandon’s russula.
Voucher saved and was submitted for sequencing.

results.notes:
A NJMA foray collection found by an unknown foray participant.
This is a strange-looking collection. It has an appearance similar to the smallish and ungainly kind of the “tylops” I am used to finding only in the sandy pine-oak barrens of the outer NJ Atlantic coastal plain. However, I wonder if it just happens to be a discolored and faded T. balloui, despite the weird yellow dried flesh beneath the cracked and worn out brown pileipellis. BTW, we do find the orange-capped balloui in the NJ Pine Barrens, though I have always wondered whether it’s the same classic taxon of the upland hardwood hardwood forests of northern NJ. As a matter of fact, I recently saw two such collections — one in Belleplain State Forest of Cape May Co. (not photographed) and one in Franklin Parker Preserve in Burlington Co. (to be posted soon).
Even though Smith’s Woods are located in the broad coastal plain of southern NJ (one of the five major ecological regions of NJ), it’s located too far west to even be on the far outskirts the core Pine Barrens ecosystem represented by its leaky sandy soils and gnarly pines and scrub oaks.1 Yet, the overall broad geology of the area where Eastampton Twp. is situated is comprised of silt, sand and clay; the only apparent difference is the age of the deposits: Cretaceous vs. Tertiary.2 However, Smith’s Woods are mostly mixed hardwoods with lot of beech, which doesn’t occur in the Pine Barrens, but, nonetheless, these deciduous woods are very different from the New England-Acadian and Northeast US Coastal forests of northern NJ.2
I did take this collection home, but regret not saving it.
References:
1 https://achekulaev.medium.com/...
2 https://www.state.nj.us/dep/njgs/njgeol.htm
